vectorData.altText: 15. Identify the class of tissue. Be specific.
That’s right! Reticular fibres dominate in reticular CT, where it forms a stroma which supports the tissue parenchyma.

Reticular CT is dominated by delicate reticular fibres, aka collagen type III. It forms an extensive network in highly cellular organs , the stroma (scaffolding), on which organs arrange their parenchyma, or functional cells
Reticular CT is dominant in the liver, kidneys, spleen, lymph nodes, smooth muscle and bone marrow

A. This picture illustrates the reticular fibre network of an organ such as a lymph node.  The cells associated with the reticular fibres are specialized fibroblasts called reticular cells, which produce and support the reticular fibres.
The open spaces illustrated between the reticular fibres would be filled with the parenchymal cells of the lymph node, largely various types of lymphocytes.
B. This is a section from a lymph node, stained to show the reticular fibres (black). The pale cells in the spaces between the reticular fibres are mostly lymphocytes, passing through the lymph node.
